<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="How We Check Our Footnotes"
  subtitle="The Library's method for verifying every citation — and what it caught this week."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="writing-methods-citations"
>
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p>
      Everything the Library publishes rests on sources: court opinions,
      statutes, state reports, archives, scholarship. A claim a reader cannot
      trace is a claim a reader has to take on faith, and this Library was
      founded on the opposite idea — that public trusts failed for two
      centuries precisely because nobody could check the books. So we hold our
      own books to the standard we ask of trustees. This page explains how.
    </p>

    <h2>One register, every book</h2>
    <p>
      Every authority we rely on — every case, statute, report, and archival
      document — lives in a single register that records what the source is,
      where the original can be found, and one more thing most bibliographies
      omit: <strong>whether we have actually verified it yet.</strong> Each
      entry is marked. Either we hold the primary document and have checked
      our quotation and page citation against it, or we are carrying the
      citation from a reliable intermediate source and say so, or the item is
      still awaiting verification and is flagged. Those flags print. When a
      page of the hornbook says <code>[VERIFY]</code>, that is the register
      showing through — a promise still being run to ground, visible to you
      at the same moment it is visible to us.
    </p>

    <h2>Harvest, verify, correct</h2>
    <p>
      The method has three motions, and they run continuously.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Harvest.</strong> We pull primary documents into the Library's
      own collection — full court opinions, session laws, agency reports —
      rather than relying on summaries or secondhand quotations. A scheduled
      task works through the queue of still-unverified authorities week after
      week.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Verify.</strong> With the primary in hand, we compare. Does the
      opinion actually contain the sentence everyone quotes from it? Is the
      page number right? Does the case actually hold what the brief said it
      held? Is the fund figure the audited value or somebody's projection?
      Every comparison is logged.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Correct.</strong> When verification finds a problem, the text is
      fixed — and the fix is recorded, not buried. Where an error had already
      reached a published page, the page says what was wrong and what changed.
      Institutions that conceal their corrections drift; institutions that
      publish them can be trusted with the next claim.
    </p>

    <h2>What the method caught this week</h2>
    <p>
      A verification pass over the Library's books and the hornbook ran this
      week. A few of its findings show why the work is worth doing.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>A famous sentence that does not exist.</strong> A line about
      trust duties — "they must be performed; they admit of no substitution;
      they admit of no addition" — circulates widely in school-trust writing,
      attributed to a 1919 United States Supreme Court decision,
      <em>Ervien v. United States</em>. We read the opinion. The sentence is
      not in it. The opinion's genuine language — duties "special and exact,"
      precluding "any supplementary or aiding sense" — is strong enough on its
      own, and that is what our books now quote. The phantom sentence has been
      removed everywhere we had repeated it.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>A fund figure that was really a forecast.</strong> One state's
      school trust fund was carried in a draft at $8.4 billion. Verification
      traced that number to a projection of future mineral royalties — not the
      fund's actual reported value, which was $7.94 billion as of December
      2025. The books now carry the audited figure, with its as-of date.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>A statistic we refused to print.</strong> A draft asserted that
      a specific number of states publish no complete accounting of their
      school trusts. It is a vivid number. It is also unsupported — no
      national survey of the question exists, and the figure traced back to an
      AI system's confident guess that had then been quoted as if it were a
      finding. The claim now states the documented reality without the
      invented precision: the absence of consolidated reporting is itself the
      finding.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>A rule against quoting ourselves.</strong> The audit also
      enforced a discipline that sounds obvious and is surprisingly easy to
      violate: our own books, model legislation, and memos are never cited as
      evidence for anything. A project that quotes itself in a circle can
      prove anything. Where a draft chapter had leaned on our own commentary,
      it now rests on the underlying cases and statutes, or says plainly that
      it is describing our proposal.
    </p>

    <h2>Where AI fits, honestly</h2>
    <p>
      AI systems do much of this work — the reading at scale, the comparing of
      quotations against opinions, the bookkeeping of hundreds of register
      entries. AI is also one of the reasons the work is necessary: as the
      phantom statistic shows, machine confidence is not evidence. The
      arrangement is the same one this Library recommends for every perpetual
      institution: let the machines do the exhaustive checking, let the rules
      be written down and public, and let humans set the standard and review
      the result. Errors found are logged and mined for patterns, so the
      process improves the way endowments are supposed to grow — compounding.
    </p>

    <h2>Help us</h2>
    <p>
      The flags you see in our drafts are open invitations. If you can supply
      a primary source, correct a citation, or catch an error we missed, write
      to the <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>. Corrections are
      verified against primary documents and carried into the next edition —
      with the change noted, in the open, the way it should be.
    </p>
  </article>
